  "recipe": {
    "description": "Chicken thighs are great when you brown them skin side down over medium to med-low heat over a longer time. Get a good deep brown color, fat is rendered out, and skin gets incredibly crispy. By doing it on a lower heat, you also run less of a risk of burning your seasonings. Then, flip the chicken and do the same thing again. Don't worry, you're not going to overcook a chicken thigh. You could put those in a 400\u00b0F oven for 4 hours and they'd still be edible.\n\nSaut\u00e9e your rice for a minute or two in the fat before adding liquid. Would need be a bad idea to drain some of the fat off too. There seems to be a little much in there. Helps develop the flavor and keeps the rice from becoming mushy. Also, don't overcook your rice. Finally, I'd add a bit of cider or wine vinegar to the cooking liquid to help add some depth of flavor and cut through some of the fat. Could also use citrus.",
